{{Infobox language | name = Dilling | nativename = Warki | states = [[Sudan]] | region = [[Nuba Mountains]] | ethnicity = [[Dilling people]] , [[Debri people]] | speakers = 11,000 | date = 2012 | ref = <ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/dil|title=Dilling|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2017-06-25}}</ref> | familycolor = Nilo-Saharan | fam2 = [[Eastern Sudanic languages|Eastern Sudanic]] | fam3 = [[Astaboran languages|Astaboran]] | fam4 = [[Nubian languages|Nubian]] | fam5 = [[Hill Nubian languages|Hill Nubian]] | iso3 = dil | glotto =dill1242 | glottorefname =Dilling }}'''Dilling''' (also Delen, Warkimbe; autonym: ''Warki'') is a [[Hill Nubian]] language spoken in the northwestern [[Nuba Mountains]] in the south of [[Sudan]]. It is spoken by around 11,000 people in the town of Dilling and surrounding hills, including Kudur. ''Ethnologue'' reports that Dilling is [[Moribund language|moribund]], with only older adults speaking the language and not using it with their children. All speakers also use [[Sudanese Arabic]]. The Dilling call themselves ''Warki'', while the Dilling speakers of Kudur call themselves ''Kwashe''.<ref name=":0" />
== Dialects == Dilling has one dialect – Debri,<ref name=":0" /> which is spoken on the mountain Gebel Debri, south of [[Ghulfan language|Ghulfan]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=P7AgAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA74|title=The Meroitic Language and Writing System|last=Rilly|first=Claude|last2=Voogt|first2=Alex de|date=2012-08-27|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=9781139560535|location=|pages=74|language=en}}</ref>
