{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Eldrid Lunden | image = EL i Delfi.jpg | imagesize = 220px | caption = Eldrid Lunden in Delphi, 2000 | pseudonym = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1940|10|5|df=y}} | birth_place = Neustdal, Norway | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = poet, essayist | nationality = Norwegian | period = | genre = Modernism | subject = | movement = | website = | signature = | awards = {{ubl| [[Nynorsk Literature Prize]] (1982) |[[Dobloug Prize]] (1989) |[[Brage Prize]] (2000) }} }} '''Eldrid Lunden''' (born 5 October 1940) is a [[Norway|Norwegian]] poet, and [[Norway]]'s first professor in creative writing, at [[Telemark University College]]. She was awarded the [[Dobloug Prize]] in 1989, and the [[Brage Prize]] honorary award in 2000.<ref name=brage-former>{{cite web|url=http://www.brageprisen.no/tekster/tidligere.shtml|title=Tidligere vinnere av Brageprisen|work=|date=|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2008-10-14|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610082646/http://www.brageprisen.no/tekster/tidligere.shtml|archivedate=2008-06-10|df=}}</ref>
Lunden belonged to the circle surrounding the modernist literary magazine ''[[Profil (literary magazine)|Profil]]''.
She was born in [[Naustdal]] and took her [[cand.philol.]] degree at the [[University of Oslo]].<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Eldrid Lunden |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Dag |last=Aanderaa |authorlink= |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=https://nbl.snl.no/Eldrid_Lunden | language=Norwegian |accessdate=26 July 2017}}</ref> She is a sister of [[Kåre Lunden]].<ref name =nbl/>
